astructures. The book shows that while modern concepts and infrastructures have come to dominate both the hydrosphere and the scholarly literature on water, longstanding popular understandings and engagements with these heterogeneous liquids have been reproduced as part of the same process. Attention to these dynamics can help us comprehend and confront the water crisis that is coming to a head in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aAnthropology. 0aBathszMexicozMexico CityxHistory. 0aEnvironmental sciences. 0aGeology. 0aGroundwaterzMexicozMexico City. 0aHistory (General). 0aMineral waterszMexicozMexico City. 0aWater resources developmentzMexicozMexico Cityy21st century. 0aWaterzMexicozMexico CityxHistory. 0aWater-supplyzMexicozMexico Cityy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  a18th century.  aacademic.  abathing.  abiology.  achemistry.  acommunity.  acultural.  acultures.  adomination.  aearly modern.  agroundwater.  ahot springs.  ahydraulics.  alaw and order.  alegal issues.  amexican tourist.  amexico city.  amexico.  amid atlantic.  amineral springs.  anatural phenomenon.  anatural world.  anature.  apolicing.  apublic baths.  arelaxation.  aresearch.  arevolution.  aspa tourism.  aspa.  atourist.  atravel mexico.  atravel.  awater.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520965393zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965393zOpen Access70423Cove